I see you're on o1js 2.4.0.  Did it work on an older version of the SDK?
You can try downgrading back to 2.3 or older and see if that resolves.  Deleting node modules shouldn't do much, but it's never too bad of an idea 😅

For debugging, you can add `Provable.log` calls in your code, which will work like console log.  You can also use any node JS debugger to step through execution.  You could run into issues if the issue is deeper than o1js.  You will find that the thread eventually enters some arcane bindings code.  But 99 times out of 100, bugs are in the JavaScript side.

yeah so I tried it on a different machine got the same error but vars reversed let me debug it more. the setup is quite cumbersome as I do not have scripts in place I will ping if I solve this error or I have written scripts for easier setup
the circuit is fully evaluated if I log the output just before the return. will investigate this more

okay so this error
```
Error: the permutation was not constructed correctly: final value
```

was my fault I was passing wrong params to the double array of balances at proving times. But I think the error should have reflected that maybe something along `length` expected vs given. I guess this also works as i was basically baking wrong constants into the circuit.

`Error: the permutation was not constructed correctly: final value` usually indicates that there is a discrepancy between compile and proving - eg the circuit was compiled for structure A but passed in was structure B during proving time. We should definitely do some work to make this clearer, unfornately types don't always catch this
We did some work on this in the past but never landed it https://github.com/o1-labs/o1js/pull/1363
